692
73:59.280 --> 74:07.740
And so if we put the two facts together, we see that every prime factor of N must divide one of the two
expressions in parentheses,

693
74:07.740 --> 74:12.690
because that's the only way
that N can divide the product.

694
74:12.690 --> 74:21.060
Now, it could be that every
single prime factor of N divides the first
expression in parentheses and not the second, but for our random A,

695
74:21.060 --> 74:27.900
that's not very likely. And so when we compute
the GCD in step four, we're likely to get the product

696
74:27.900 --> 74:32.760
of some of the prime
factors of N, but not all.

697
74:32.760 --> 74:37.710
To analyze this carefully
requires some number theory, but it is pretty basic number theory.

698
74:37.710 --> 74:43.560
So if you find number
theory to be interesting and you'd like to learn more about it, try working through this analysis.

699
74:43.560 --> 74:48.930
Working through things like this is an excellent way to learn more, but I will leave that to you.

700
74:48.930 --> 74:57.030
And that's the end of the lesson. In this lesson, we covered
the phase estimation problem, how we can solve it efficiently
on a quantum computer,

701
74:57.030 --> 75:04.200
and how we can apply the solution to obtain a polynomial
cost quantum algorithm for integer factorization.

702
75:04.200 --> 75:09.150
I hope you'll join me for the next lesson, which is on Grover's
quantum searching algorithm.

703
75:09.150 --> 75:10.100
Goodbye until then.
